# 6) Probability — ML heart

If statistics is “data ardham”, probability is “uncertainty ni mathematically handle cheyyadam”.

Real world deterministic kaadu.

- spam or not spam
- fraud or not fraud
- disease or no disease
- user click chesthada?
- loan default chesthada?
- next word enti?

Ivi all uncertainty-based problems.

So probability is not just dice game.  
It is **belief under uncertainty**.

---

## 6.1 Probability basic intuition

Probability ante chance ani simple ga cheppachu.  
Kani ML angle lo:

**“Given information, event gurinchi mana confidence measure”**

Example:
Rain tomorrow = 0.8  
Ante guaranteed kaadu.  
But strong confidence.

ML lo predictions often probabilities ga vastayi:
- class 1 probability
- click-through probability
- churn probability
- toxicity score
- fraud score

These are used for ranking and decision thresholds.

---

## 6.2 Conditional Probability — context vachaka chance marutundi

### Meaning
“A jarigindani telisinappudu B probability enti?”

Notation gurinchi kaadu, intuition important.

Example:
Without any info, dengue chance low.  
But:
- fever undi
- platelet low
- mosquito exposure undi

Appudu chance marutundi.

### Why this is huge in ML?
Almost every ML model context-based.

Examples:
- user clicked ad given device=mobile
- default probability given low credit score
- disease probability given symptoms
- word probability given previous words
- fraud probability given transaction location mismatch

So ML models are basically conditional pattern learners.

---

## 6.3 Bayes Theorem — new evidence vachaka belief update

Bayes is very important.  
Formula kante concept chala powerful.

### Core intuition
First you have prior belief.  
Then new evidence vasthundi.  
Appudu belief ni update chesthav.

### Real example
Rare disease test positive.

Many people mistake:
“test positive ante disease definitely undi”

Kadu.

Need:
- disease base rate
- test sensitivity
- false positive rate

Bayes chepthundi:
Evidence ni context tho combine cheyyali.

### ML usage
- Naive Bayes
- spam classification
- medical diagnosis
- fault detection
- ranking systems
- probabilistic reasoning
- Bayesian updates in monitoring

### Senior insight
Bayes teaches humility:
Evidence alone kaadu, **base rates** kuda matter.

This is critical in imbalanced problems.

---

# 7) Distributions — data shape ni ardham chesukovadam

Single summary numbers chalu kaadu.  
Data full shape important.

Distribution tells:
- where values cluster
- skew unda?
- tails heavy aa?
- multiple groups unnaya?
- rare events pattern enti?

---

## 7.1 Normal Distribution — bell curve

### Why famous?
Chala natural phenomena approximate normal behavior chupistayi:
- height
- noise
- measurement errors
- aggregated effects

### Properties
- symmetric
- mean ≈ median ≈ mode
- center lo ekkuva values
- extremes lo takkuva values

### ML importance
Many methods implicitly or explicitly normality-like behavior ni assume chestayi:
- z-score interpretation
- classical statistical tests
- linear model residual assumptions
- Gaussian models
- control charts

### Important caution
Real-world data often not normal:
- salaries skewed
- prices skewed
- counts discrete
- user activity long-tail

So “normal distribution” ni blind ga assume cheyyakudadhu.

---

## 7.2 Binomial Distribution — yes/no repeated trials

Example:
100 emails lo spam count entha?
10 ad impressions lo clicks enni?
20 users lo कितने convert ayyaru?

Whenever each trial:
- two outcomes
- same probability-ish
- repeated independent attempts

Then binomial thinking useful.

### ML / product relevance
- CTR modeling
- conversion counts
- experiment success rates
- classification event counts

---

## 7.3 Poisson Distribution — event counts in interval

Example:
- one hour lo customer support tickets enni?
- one day lo failures enni?
- one minute lo incoming calls enni?
- one page lo OCR errors enni?

Poisson useful when rare events occur over time or space.

### Product examples
- server incident counts
- defect counts
- transaction failures
- arrivals per unit time

### Why this matters?
Because some targets are counts, not continuous values.  
Appudu linear regression kanna count models better.

---

# 8) Correlation & Covariance — relation unte enti, cause aa?

---

## 8.1 Covariance

Covariance says:
Rendu variables kalisi ela move avuthunnayi?

- one up, other up → positive
- one up, other down → negative

But scale-dependent.  
Interpretation direct ga kastam.

---

## 8.2 Correlation

Correlation is normalized covariance.  
So easier to read.

- +1 close → strong positive relation
- -1 close → strong negative relation
- 0 close → no linear relation

### Example
Study hours ↑ → marks ↑  
Likely positive correlation.

### ML usage
- feature selection
- redundancy detection
- multicollinearity inspection
- exploratory analysis
- dimensionality reduction prep

### Major caution
Correlation ≠ causation

Ice cream sales పెరిగాయి, drowning పెరిగింది.  
Ice cream వల్ల drowning కాదు.  
Common hidden factor = summer.

### Engineering-level significance
If two features strongly correlated:
- model unstable అవ్వచ్చు
- linear coefficients unreliable అవ్వచ్చు
- duplicate information ఉండచ్చు

So we may:
- drop one feature
- combine features
- regularize model
- use PCA

### Senior caveat
Correlation mostly linear relation.  
Nonlinear relation miss avvachu.  
So scatter plots and mutual info kuda useful.

